The interest rate is compounded monthly; therefore, we will divide the 1.25% interest rate to twelve, representing the number of months in a year. Hence we will express the rate in the following equation:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Rate} &= \dfrac{0.0125}{12}
\end{aligned}$$

Let's now calculate the future value for the six months using the introductory rate of 1.25%.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Future value} &=\$8,000\times(1 + \dfrac{0.0125}{12})^{6}
\\[10pt]
&= \$8,000\times1.00627
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\$8,050.13}
\end{aligned}$$

Therefore, the future value of the payment for the first six months is $8,050.13.

Similar to the first calculation, the compounding period is six, and the interest rate is divided by twelve representing the number of months in a year. Hence, we will use the following equation as the rate for the next six months' future value calculation:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Rate} &= \dfrac{0.178}{12}
\end{aligned}$$

Let's now calculate the future value for the next six months using the rate of 17.8%

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Future value} &=\$8,050.13\times(1 + \dfrac{0.178}{12})^{6}
\\[10pt]
&= \$8,050.13\times1.09237
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\$8,793.69}
\end{aligned}$$

Hence, the future value of the $8,000 from the credit card is $8,793.69.

Last, now that we have the future value of the initial balance of $8,000 from our account, to determine the interest expense for the first year, subtract the initial balance to the future value. Hence we will use the following equation:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Interest expense} &=\text{Future value balance}-\text{Initial balance}

\end{aligned}$$
